ce:section.ce:para:
The nitrogen adsorption-desorption isotherms of GQDs@Fe3O4 (Fig. 5

                        ) and BET analysis (Table 1
                        ) elucidate critical textural characteristics that underscore its appropriateness for adsorption applications. The adsorbent exhibited a Type I isotherm curve, with a specific surface area (SBET) of 22.10 m2 g−1, indicating a reasonable surface area available for adsorption, a trait commonly observed in composite materials. The mean pore diameter of 17.37 nm classifies the material as mesoporous, a characteristic that enhances the diffusion and adsorption of molecules, especially for larger molecules [50]. Furthermore, the pore volume of 0.151 cm3 g−1 reflects the material's ability to host a considerable quantity of adsorbate. Collectively, these attributes imply that GQDs@Fe3O4 is a promising candidate for pollutant adsorption.
